Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of large architectural features and the primary deposition of fluvial wash. Debris accumulates in the Shrine Room followed by major collapse. The West Walkway Wall collapses and the Residential Quarter is destroyed.

Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of 512. Fill accumulates following the disuse of the canalization systems. The remains of two bodies are found in the upper level fluvial deposits. Localized burning in some areas.
XIII

This soil fill comprises the majority of the fill of the room cut into the East Perimeter Wall. Its Munsell color is Red, 2.5YR5/6, and it included bones, scattered bits of charcoal, shells, slag, many stones of varying sizes, including parts of ashlars, and an extremely large amount of pottery. The soil was fairly loose, and was most likely largely wash down from above the bedrock ledge under which it was deposited. A number of complete or nearly complete ceramic vessels were found in this locus, including cups, bowls and lacrymatories, all rather small vessels, although parts of larger storage vessels and amphorae were also found. One interesting find was a complete and virtually brand new small bowl (Special Find #9, Seq. No. SP 84232) found wedged behind the south side of the Oven/ tabun (Locus 10). The position of this cup seems to suggest that it may not have merely washed down but actually may be in situ. The erosive wash down presumably moved mainly from north to south and from east to west (due to the natural ledge in the overhanging bedrock, which shielded the southeast corner of the trench, but not the northeast), whereas this vessel would have had to have washed in from the south toward the north. Therefore, it may have been placed behind the Oven/ tabun intentionally, either for convenient access, storage, or as support.
